<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>DISH AND T-MOBILE SAID TO BE DISCUSSING MERGER</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The American media and communications sector could see yet another big merger soon, <a href="//www.wsj.com/articles/dish-network-in-merger-talks-with-t-mobile-us-1433383285"> The Wall Street Journal reports</a>, this time involving <b>Dish Network and T-Mobile</b>. Citing people familiar with the matter, the newspaper reports that the talks are in âthe formative stageâ but that the two sides are in close agreement about the structure of the enlarged company, with Charlie Ergen, Dishâs chief executive, as the new entityâs chairman and John Legere, T-Mobileâs chief executive, as the new chief executive. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">However, the two companies are still <b>hashing out the price and the financing terms</b>, The Wall Street Journal writes. If they agree on a figure, it is likely to be high: T-Mobile, the countryâs fourth-largest wireless carrier, has a market capitalization of about $31 billion, and Dish, the countryâs second-largest satellite TV operator, has a market capitalization of $33 billion, according to the newspaper.<br />
</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>ELLIOTT MANAGEMENT TAKES ON SAMSUNG GROUP</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The activist hedge fund Elliott Management has decided to challenge the South Korean conglomerate the Samsung Group by buying a 7 percent stake in Samsung C&#038;T, a construction and industrial investment company, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/06/05/business/dealbook/an-activist-investor-takes-aim-at-bid-for-samsung.html"> Neil Gough writes in DealBook</a>. Samsung C&#038;T, which holds a significant stake in Samsung Electronics, the conglomerateâs flagship unit, is currently the target of an $8 billion takeover bid by Cheil Industries, the conglomerateâs de facto holding company. The Samsung Group involves a complex network of dozens of companies, and analysts described Cheilâs offer as a <b>move designed to cement the position of the groupâs heir-apparent</b>, Jay Y. Lee, who is vice chairman of Samsung Electronics. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On Thursday, after buying the stake in Samsung C&#038;T, Elliott said Cheilâs all-shares takeover offer âsignificantly undervalues Samsung C&#038;T and that the terms are neither fair to nor in the best interests of Samsung C&#038;Tâs shareholders.â âIt is a <b>rare glimpse of investor activism</b> in a region where such campaigns are seldom seen and have met with mixed results in the past,â Mr. Gough writes. However, this is not the first time Elliott has attempted to change the way an Asian business is run, Mr. Gough noted. Last year, Elliott had built up a small stake in the Bank of East Asia, which is controlled by the family of David Li, but that stake was diluted after the bank sold new shares to the Sumitomo Mitsui Financial Group of Japan. Elliott sued the Bank of East Asia over the share sale, and the lawsuit is still pending in Hong Kong.<br />
</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>POSITIVE SIGNALS ON GREEK DEBT DEAL</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> European leaders were sounding more optimistic on Wednesday that Greece and its creditors would soon agree on a bailout deal, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/06/04/business/international/greek-debt-tsipras-juncker-imf-european-commission.html"> Liz Alderman and Jack Ewing write in The New York Times</a>.  In one of the strongest signals of a potential compromise, Mario Draghi, the president of the European Central Bank, one of Greeceâs creditors, said that <b> âsocial fairnessâ</b> â a new phrase from him â should be an element in the program that Greece will need to accept, and he indicated a willingness to slightly ease the fiscal targets that Greece has been asked to meet. President FranÃ§ois Hollande of France told reporters on Wednesday at the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development in Paris that âit is a matter of <b>a few days or even hours from a possible settlement</b>.â  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Prime Minister Alexis Tsipras of Greece described a telephone conversation with Mr. Hollande and Chancellor Angela Merkel of Germany as âconstructive.â Mr. Tsipras met on Wednesday evening in Brussels with Jean-Claude Juncker, the president of the European Commission, and Jeroen Dijsselbloem, president of the Eurogroup of finance ministers, to discuss proposals to release 7.2 billion euros, or about $8.1 billion, from Greeceâs existing international bailout program. Mr. Dijsselbloem later described the meeting as âgood.â Mr. Tsipras told reporters that there had been <b>progress on the so-called primary surplus</b>, or the amount of revenue that Greece is required to hold in its coffers after expenses have been paid and before servicing its debt.<br />
</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>ON THE AGENDA</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> <b>Weekly jobless claims data</b> is out at 8:30 a.m. <b> Daniel Tarullo</b>, a Federal Reserve governor, will speak at noon at the Institute of International Finance North America Summit in New York, which also features <b> Laurence D. Fink</b>, chief executive of BlackRock, and <b> Douglas Flint</b>, the chairman of HSBC. <b>Christine Lagarde</b>, the managing director of the International Monetary Fund, holds a news conference at 9:30 a.m. on the American economy. <b>Glenn Youngkin</b>, president and chief operating officer of Carlyle Group, will be on Bloomberg Television at 8:40 a.m.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b> On the Hill:</b> The Senate Banking Committee holds a hearing titled Oversight of the Export-Import Bank of the United States,â at 10 a.m.<br />
</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>UNASKED QUESTIONS IN JUSTICE MEETING WITH GOLDMAN</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> On March 5, 2010, Lanny A. Breuer, then the assistant attorney general for the criminal division, gathered some of his prosecutors to meet with executives from Goldman Sachs, including David N. Lawrence, who at the time was global head of the companyâs business intelligence group, according to a document <a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2015/06/03/business/dealbook/document-justice-dept-memo-on-goldman-meeting.html"> obtained by Matthew Goldstein and Nathaniel Popper of DealBook</a>. At the time, the financial crisis was taking a heavy toll on the economy, but the hourlong meeting at the Justice Department had nothing to do with the crisis or with Goldmanâs role in marketing securities backed by mortgage loans made to borrowers with shaky credit histories, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/06/04/business/dealbook/2010-goldman-justice-dept-meeting-said-to-have-covered-terrorism-funding-but-not-financial-crisis.html"> Mr. Goldstein and Mr. Popper write</a>. Instead, the gathering focused <b>exclusively on the subject of terrorism financing</b>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The meeting may revive questions about the <b>Justice Departmentâs priorities after the financial crisis</b>, Mr. Goldstein and Mr. Popper write. Mr. Breuerâs tenure, which ended in early 2013, was marked by criticism that his office did not do enough to hold prominent Wall Street bankers accountable for the crisis. âI applaud him for going to experts on money laundering, but how could you resist not asking even one question about the thing on everyoneâs mind?â said Erik Gordon, a professor at the Ross School of Business of the University of Michigan. âItâs <b>a real head-scratcher</b> how he could be in the room with three or four people from Goldman and not take advantage to ask them about the financial crisis.â </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The email invitation for the meeting surfaced as a result of a Freedom of Information Act request to review Mr. Breuerâs electronic calendar. The agency was asked for a list of meetings between him and representatives of Goldman, JPMorgan Chase, Bank of America and the American International Group â institutions that played significant roles in the run-up to the financial crisis.<br />
</p>
</div>
